  <bgc:methodology blockPublic="no">
    <bgc:introduction input="textarea">Core set of stand structural attributes (SSA) that characterize the structure of forest EPs, and may contribute to explain local biodiversity.</bgc:introduction>
    <bgc:measurements>
      <bgc:theory input="textarea">The dataset comprises 32 attributes of forests stand structure, which we consider to be concise and meaningful. The SSA quantify (i) stand maturity, (ii) tree size heterogeneity, (iii) compositional heterogeneity, (iv) horizontal heterogeneity, and (v) combinations of tree size, compositional and horizontal heterogeneity. Out of the 32 SSAs 12 are position-dependent. We quantified the position-independent metrics (20) for all EPs and the position-dependent for the 135 EPs with mapped stem locations.

SSA were calculated based on single tree data (species identity, diameter at breast height and location) of the initial forest inventory (2nd phase of the Exploratories from 2008 to 2010 by PI Schulze) and of the “forest inventory completion campaign” conducted afterwards (22 EPs). Users should be aware that the complete forest inventory lasted a number of years. Note that the SSAs are not that meaningful for thickets, as only trees with dbh &gt;= 7 cm were inventoried.

The dataset is topically structured.
A) Position-independent metrics
- 6 stand summary properties – stand maturity in even-aged stands
- 3 diameter distribution properties - tree size heterogeneity
- 3 diameter class properties (4 cm width) - tree size heterogeneity
- 5 tree species diversity properties - compositional heterogeneity
- 3 properties of tree species in diameter classes (4 cm width) - compositional tree size heterogeneity
B) Position-dependent metrics
- 5 metrics of horizontal variation of stand summary properties (10 m x 10 m raster cells)
- 3 indices of tree distribution – horizontal heterogeneity: regular to clumped
- 4 two factor indices - horizontal heterogeneity of tree size or composition

We also calculated other metrics (like Gini coefficient of dbh) which are not included in this dataset, as we found them to be redundant. Please contact us if you need specific metrics or e.g. a different resolution for horizontal variation.

Due to skewness some SSAs should be transformed prior to statistical analysis, e.g.
ssm.N &lt;- sqrt(ssm.N)
sp.N.1D &lt;- log(sp.N.1D)
sp.N.2D &lt;- log(sp.N.2D)
sp.BA.1D &lt;- log(sp.BA.1D)
sp.BA.2D &lt;- log(sp.BA.2D)
r10.noTree &lt;- log(1 + r10.noTree)
</bgc:theory>
      <bgc:type input="textarea">Analysis of original data.

Measurement period of individual plots is specified in BExIS  17687.</bgc:type>
    </bgc:measurements>
